<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-06-04T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-06-04T04:00:00-05:00" n="429" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d429">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/3365: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Tenney</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-06-04T17:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">June 4,
                                            1920—5 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received June 4—11:40
                                    a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>126. With financial aid of Japanese, Tuan Ch’i-jui and Hsu Shucheng
                                are forming military force to take aggressive action against
                                supporters of Canton government. The President may give up office.
                                He feels disheartened. As yet formation of cabinet is not completed.
                                Condition of country is serious.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Tenney</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>